(1, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Delhi', 'Delhi4.JPG, Delhi6.JPG, Delhi3.JPG', 'Madhya Pradesh, Haryana', 'In addition to the Taj Mahal, India Gate, and Red Fort, Delhi has many other famous places that are worth visiting. One such place is the Qutub Minar, a towering 73-meter-tall minaret that was built in the 12th century. The complex also includes the Quwwat-ul-Islam Mosque, one of the oldest surviving mosques in India.\r\n\r\nAnother popular tourist attraction in Delhi is the Lotus Temple, a Bahá\'í House of Worship that is shaped like a lotus flower. It is a symbol of peace, purity, and unity, and attracts visitors from all over the world.\r\n\r\nFor those interested in history, the National Museum is a must-visit destination. It houses a vast collection of artifacts, sculptures, paintings, and other items that showcase the rich cultural heritage of India.', 'Delhi is not just about monuments and museums. The city has plenty of other attractions that offer a glimpse into its vibrant culture and traditions. One such place is Chandni Chowk, a bustling market that is famous for its narrow lanes, colorful shops, and street food. Here, you can savor some of the best street food in India, such as chaat, parathas, and kebabs.\r\n\r\nAnother must-visit destination in Delhi is the Akshardham Temple, a sprawling complex that showcases the best of Indian architecture, art, and spirituality. It features a grand temple, a musical fountain, a boat ride, and a cultural exhibition that is sure to leave you spellbound.\r\n\r\nFor those who love nature, the Delhi Zoo is a great place to visit. It is home to a wide variety of animals, including tigers, lions, elephants, and birds, and is a perfect place to spend a day with family and friends.', '2296 km', '40 hours by road, 1 hour by flight', 'Delhi is well-connected to the rest of India and the world by air, road, and rail. Indira Gandhi International Airport is one of the busiest airports in India and receives flights from all major cities in the world. The city also has a well-developed network of roads and highways that connect it to the neighboring states and cities. National Highway 44 is the most popular route that connects Delhi to Tamilnadu and passes through Madhya Pradesh and Haryana.\r\n\r\nDelhi also has several railway stations that connect it to different parts of India. The major railway stations in Delhi are New Delhi Railway Station, Old Delhi Railway Station, and Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station.', 'Delhi is a city that has something for everyone. Whether you are interested in history, culture, art, food, or nature, you will find plenty of things to do and see here. The city\'s monuments and museums are a testament to its rich cultural heritage, while its markets and restaurants offer a glimpse into its vibrant present. From the towering Qutub Minar to the colorful streets of Chandni Chowk, Delhi is a city that is full of surprises and delights. So, whether you are a first-time visitor or a seasoned traveler, make sure to include Delhi in your itinerary and experience the best of India.'),
(2, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'uttar_pradesh1.JPG,uttar_pradesh2.JPG', 'Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh', 'Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, Fatehpur Sikri, Akbar\'s Tomb, Jama Masjid', 'Uttar Pradesh is home to several famous tourist attractions, including the Taj Mahal, one of the Seven Wonders of the World. This stunning marble mausoleum was built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal. Agra Fort is another popular tourist attraction, which was built by the Mughal emperor Akbar in the 16th century. The fort has several palaces, mosques, and gardens and offers a panoramic view of the Taj Mahal.\r\n\r\nFatehpur Sikri is another must-visit destination in Uttar Pradesh. It was built by the Mughal emperor Akbar as his capital and has several impressive structures, such as the Buland Darwaza, Diwan-i-Khas, and Diwan-i-Am.\r\n\r\nFor those interested in history and architecture, the tomb of Akbar in Sikandra is a must-visit destination. The tomb is a magnificent example of Mughal architecture and features several intricate carvings and inscriptions', 'The travel distance from Tamil Nadu to Uttar Pradesh is approximately 2250 km by road.', 'The travel time from Tamil Nadu to Uttar Pradesh depends on the mode of transportation. By road, it takes around 40-45 hours to reach Uttar Pradesh, while by train, it takes around 24-30 hours, depending on the route and the train.', 'Uttar Pradesh is well-connected to the rest of India by air, rail, and road. The major airports in Uttar Pradesh are located in Lucknow, Varanasi, and Agra, which receive regular flights from all major cities in India.\r\n\r\nThere are several railway stations in Uttar Pradesh, including Lucknow, Agra, and Varanasi, which are well-connected to different parts of India. The journey from Tamil Nadu to Uttar Pradesh can be made by taking a direct train or by taking a connecting train from Delhi or another major city.\r\n\r\nBy road, the journey from Tamil Nadu to Uttar Pradesh can be made by taking National Highway 44, which connects the two states and passes through Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Maharashtra, and Madhya Pradesh.\r\n\r\n', ' Uttar Pradesh is a state that is rich in history, culture, and traditions. The state is home to several famous monuments, including the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and Fatehpur Sikri, which are known for their stunning architecture and historical significance. The state is also famous for its delicious cuisine, colorful festivals, and vibrant markets.\r\n\r\nWhether you are interested in history, culture, food, or nature, Uttar Pradesh has something for everyone. From the magnificent Taj Mahal to the bustling markets of Agra and Lucknow, the state offers a unique blend of tradition and modernity. So, whether you are a first-time visitor or a seasoned traveler, make sure to include Uttar Pradesh in your itinerary and experience the best of India.'),
(3, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Rajasthan', 'rajasthan1.JPG, rajasthan2.JPG', 'Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Maharashtra, Gujarat', 'Jaipur, Udaipur, Jaisalmer, Jodhpur, Pushkar, Ajmer, Mount Abu', ' Rajasthan is a state that is known for its rich culture, traditions, and heritage. The state is home to several famous tourist destinations, including the Pink City of Jaipur, the Lake City of Udaipur, the Golden City of Jaisalmer, and the Blue City of Jodhpur.\r\n\r\nJaipur, the capital of Rajasthan, is famous for its stunning palaces, forts, and monuments. The City Palace, Hawa Mahal, Amber Fort, and Jantar Mantar are some of the must-visit tourist attractions in Jaipur.\r\n\r\nUdaipur, also known as the Lake City, is famous for its beautiful lakes, palaces, and temples. The City Palace, Jag Mandir, Lake Pichola, and Fateh Sagar Lake are some of the popular tourist attractions in Udaipur.\r\n\r\nJaisalmer, known as the Golden City, is famous for its sand dunes, forts, and palaces. The Jaisalmer Fort, Patwon ki Haveli, Gadisar Lake, and Sam Sand Dunes are some of the must-visit tourist attractions in Jaisalmer.\r\n\r\nJodhpur, known as the Blue City, is famous for its blue-painted houses, forts, and palaces. The Mehrangarh Fort, Umaid Bhawan Palace, Jaswant Thada, and Mandore Gardens are some of the popular tourist attractions in Jodhpur.\r\n\r\nOther popular tourist destinations in Rajasthan include the holy city of Pushkar, the historic city of Ajmer, and the hill station of Mount Abu.', ' The travel distance from Tamil Nadu to Rajasthan is approximately 2600 km by road.', 'The travel time from Tamil Nadu to Rajasthan depends on the mode of transportation. By road, it takes around 45-50 hours to reach Rajasthan, while by train, it takes around 40-50 hours, depending on the route and the train.', 'Rajasthan is well-connected to the rest of India by air, rail, and road. The major airports in Rajasthan are located in Jaipur, Udaipur, and Jodhpur, which receive regular flights from all major cities in India.\r\n\r\nThere are several railway stations in Rajasthan, including Jaipur, Jodhpur, Udaipur, and Ajmer, which are well-connected to different parts of India. The journey from Tamil Nadu to Rajasthan can be made by taking a direct train or by taking a connecting train from Delhi or another major city.\r\n\r\nBy road, the journey from Tamil Nadu to Rajasthan can be made by taking National Highway 44 and National Highway 48, which connect the two states and pass through Karnataka, Maharashtra, and Gujarat.', 'Rajasthan is a state that is known for its colorful culture, rich history, and beautiful architecture. From the stunning palaces and forts to the beautiful lakes and sand dunes, the state offers a unique blend of history, culture, and nature.\r\n\r\nWhether you are interested in history, culture, or nature, Rajasthan has something for everyone. From the vibrant markets of Jaipur to the beautiful lakes of Udaipur, the state offers a unique experience that cannot be found anywhere else in India.\r\n\r\nSo, whether you are a first-time visitor or a seasoned traveler, make sure to include Rajasthan in your itinerary and experience the best of India. The state is sure to leave you mesmerized with its stunning beauty and warm hospitality.'),
(4, 'Tamil Nadu', 'Punjab', 'punjab1.JPG, punjab2.JPG', 'Our journey will take us from Tamil Nadu in the southernmost part of India, through the central states of Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh, and finally to the northwestern state of Punjab. Along the way, we will make several stops to visit some of the most famous and culturally significant sites in each state', 'In Tamil Nadu, we will explore the charming city of Chennai, known for its beautiful beaches, historic temples, and bustling markets. Some of the most famous attractions in Chennai include the Kapaleeswarar Temple, Fort St. George, and the Marina Beach.\r\n\r\nAs we travel north, we will pass through the state of Maharashtra and stop in the city of Mumbai, often referred to as the \"City of Dreams\". Mumbai is famous for its colonial architecture, vibrant nightlife, and delicious street food. Some of the must-visit attractions in Mumbai include the Gateway of India, the Elephanta Caves, and the famous Marine Drive.\r\n\r\nNext, we will travel through the state of Madhya Pradesh, stopping at the city of Indore. Indore is famous for its rich cultural heritage, historic monuments, and delicious cuisine. Some of the most popular attractions in Indore include the Rajwada Palace, the Lal Baag Palace, and the Kanch Mandir.\r\n\r\nFinally, we will reach our destination in the northwestern state of Punjab, where we will visit the iconic Golden Temple in Amritsar, one of the most sacred sites for the Sikh community. We will also explore the historic Jallianwala Bagh, where a tragic massacre took place in 1919, and the Wagah Border, which separates India and Pakistan and hosts a daily flag lowering ceremony.', 'Charminar, Golconda Fort, Ramoji Film City, Kanha Tiger Reserve, Sanchi Stupa', 'The total distance of this journey is approximately 2900 kilometers', 'it can take anywhere from 50-60 hours of driving time, depending on traffic and road conditions. Alternatively, you can also take a flight from Chennai to Amritsar, which takes approximately 3 hours.', 'If you are planning to travel from Tamil Nadu to Punjab, there are two main ways to reach the state. The first is by road, which is a great option for those who want to explore the countryside and enjoy road trips. You can take National Highway 44, which passes through Hyderabad and Nagpur before reaching Punjab. This route takes approximately 42 hours of travel time. The second way to reach Punjab is by taking a flight to Sri Guru Ram Dass Jee International Airport in Amritsar, which is well-connected to major cities in India. The flight takes around 2 hours of travel time. Once you reach Punjab, you will find a plethora of cultural and historical sites to explore, including the famous Taj Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri, and Golden Temple. The Taj Mahal is one of the most famous monuments in India, known for its magnificent beauty and architecture. Fatehpur Sikri is another popular tourist destination, known for its red sandstone architecture and historical significance. The Golden Temple, located in Amritsar, is a significant religious site for Sikhs and attracts thousands of visitors every day. Apart from these famous places, there are several other tourist attractions in the region, such as the Charminar and Golconda Fort in Hyderabad, Ramoji Film City in Hyderabad, Kanha Tiger Reserve in Madhya Pradesh, and Sanchi Stupa in Bhopal.', 'Punjab, located in the northwestern part of India, is a state rich in history and culture. The state is known for its magnificent monuments, temples, and museums, including the famous Taj Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri, and Golden Temple. The state is well-connected by road and air and can be reached by National Highway 44 or by taking a flight to Sri Guru Ram Dass Jee International Airport in Amritsar. Once you arrive in Punjab, you can explore the various tourist destinations, such as the Charminar and Golconda Fort in Hyderabad, Ramoji Film City in Hyderabad, Kanha Tiger Reserve in Madhya Pradesh, and Sanchi Stupa in Bhopal. The Golden Temple in Amritsar is a must-visit site, known for its religious significance and architectural beauty. Overall, Punjab is a state that should not be missed, with its rich history and cultural heritage that showcase the diversity and beauty of India.'),
(5, 'Kerala', 'Delhi', 'kerala1.JPG,kerala2.JPG', 'Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Delhi.', 'Once you arrive in Delhi, you\'ll be in the heart of India and surrounded by countless tourist destinations. Some of the must-visit places include the iconic India Gate, the historical Red Fort, the beautiful Lotus Temple, the Qutub Minar, and the magnificent Akshardham Temple. Delhi is also famous for its delicious street food, and you can explore some of the famous food streets like Chandni Chowk, Karim\'s, and Paranthe Wali Gali.', ' In addition to the famous places, Delhi also has many other tourist attractions to offer. The city is known for its vibrant street markets, such as Chandni Chowk and Connaught Place, which are great places to shop for local handicrafts and souvenirs. You can also visit the Akshardham Temple, which is a massive temple complex that showcases the rich spiritual and cultural heritage of India. Another popular destination is the Humayun\'s Tomb, which is a beautiful mausoleum that was built in the 16th century. The Jama Masjid is also a must-visit destination, being one of the largest mosques in India. Finally, you can visit the National Museum, which is home to a vast collection of art and artifacts that showcase the history of India.\r\n\r\nOverall, travelling from Kerala to Delhi is an exciting and fulfilling experience. With so many famous places and tourist attractions to explore, Delhi is a city that should be on every traveler\'s bucket list.', 'The distance between Kerala and Delhi is approximately 2,700 kilometers.', 'By air, it takes about 3 hours to reach Delhi from Kerala. By train, it takes approximately 40-45 hours depending on the type of train and class of travel.', 'If you\'re traveling from Kerala to Delhi, there are two main modes of transportation - air and train. The fastest and most convenient way is to take a direct flight from Cochin International Airport to Indira Gandhi International Airport in Delhi, which takes about 3 hours. You can also take a train from the major railway stations in Kerala such as Thiruvananthapuram Central, Ernakulam Junction or Kozhikode and arrive at the New Delhi Railway Station or the Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station in Delhi. The train journey takes approximately 40-45 hours depending on the type of train and class of travel. En route, you\'ll pass through some of India\'s most beautiful states, such as Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, and Uttar Pradesh.', 'Kerala, also known as \"God\'s Own Country,\" is a beautiful state located in the southern part of India. The state is known for its picturesque landscapes, beautiful beaches, serene backwaters, and rich cultural heritage. Once you arrive in Delhi, you\'ll be in the bustling capital of India, where you\'ll have the opportunity to explore some of the country\'s most famous landmarks and attractions. Whether you choose to travel by air or train, the journey from Kerala to Delhi is an experience in itself, as you pass through some of India\'s most vibrant and diverse states.'),
(6, 'Kerala', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Gokul1.JPG,Gokul2.JPG', 'Bangalore, Hyderabad,Kerala, Karnataka, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh Nagpur', 'Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, Fatehpur Sikri, Mehtab Bagh, Jama Masjid, Delhi Gate', 'Backwaters of Alleppey: The backwaters of Alleppey are a network of canals, lagoons, and lakes that run parallel to the Arabian Sea. Tourists can enjoy a houseboat ride, witness traditional fishing techniques, and explore the lush green surroundings.\r\nHampi: Hampi is a UNESCO World Heritage Site known for its well-preserved ruins of the Vijayanagara Empire. It features numerous ancient temples, palaces, and other structures.\r\nEllora Caves: The Ellora Caves are a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in Maharashtra. These rock-cut caves feature intricate sculptures and carvings, including the famous Kailash Temple.\r\nKhajuraho Temples: The Khajuraho Temples are a group of Hindu and Jain temples known for their intricate carvings depicting erotic and sensual scenes. They are located in Madhya Pradesh and were built between the 10th and 12th centuries.', ' 2,770 km', '45 hours by road, 4 hours by flight', 'If you are looking to travel from Kerala to Uttar Pradesh, there are two main ways to reach the state. The first is by road, using National Highway 44, which connects the two states and passes through Karnataka, Maharashtra, and Madhya Pradesh. This route is a great option for those who enjoy road trips and want to explore the countryside along the way. The second way to reach Uttar Pradesh is by taking a flight to Indira Gandhi International Airport in Delhi, followed by a domestic flight to Agra or Lucknow. This is a much quicker option, taking only 4 hours of travel time, but it is also more expensive than driving. Once you arrive in Uttar Pradesh, you will find a wealth of cultural and historical sites to explore, including the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, Fatehpur Sikri, Mehtab Bagh, Jama Masjid, and Delhi Gate. The Taj Mahal is a must-see attraction, known as one of the most beautiful buildings in the world. Agra Fort, another UNESCO World Heritage Site, is a massive red sandstone fort that was once the residence of Mughal emperors. Fatehpur Sikri is a ghost town that was once the capital of the Mughal Empire, while Mehtab Bagh is a beautiful garden located opposite the Taj Mahal. Jama Masjid is one of the largest mosques in India and Delhi Gate is an impressive gateway to the city of Agra.', ' A journey from Kerala to Uttar Pradesh is a wonderful opportunity to explore the diverse culture and history of India. Kerala is known for its picturesque landscapes, serene backwaters, and exotic wildlife. Thekkady and Munnar are two popular tourist destinations in Kerala, known for their natural beauty and tea plantations. Kochi, also known as the Queen of the Arabian Sea, is a vibrant city that blends modernity with tradition, with its historic forts, palaces, and Chinese fishing nets. From Kochi, you can travel to Bengaluru and then to Hyderabad, which are both famous for their historic landmarks, cuisine, and nightlife. Nagpur is also a popular stopover, known for its beautiful lakes and wildlife sanctuaries. The final destination in this journey is Agra, home to the iconic Taj Mahal, one of the Seven Wonders of the World. Agra is also known for its historic forts and palaces, including the Agra Fort and Fatehpur Sikri. Overall, this journey promises to be an unforgettable experience, offering a glimpse into the rich cultural heritage of India.'),
(7, 'Kerala', 'Rajasthan', 'rajasthann1.JPG, rajasthann2.JPG', 'Kochi, Bangalore, Hyderabad, Mumbai, Udaipur, Jaipur', 'City Palace of Udaipur, Amer Fort in Jaipur, Lake Pichola in Udaipur', 'Hawa Mahal in Jaipur: The Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is a beautiful pink sandstone palace in Jaipur, Rajasthan. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it is a five-story palace with 953 small windows or jharokhas, which were used by royal ladies to observe the street below without being seen. The intricate latticework and architecture of the palace are a sight to behold, and it is a popular destination for tourists visiting Jaipur.\r\n\r\nJaisalmer Fort in Jaisalmer: The Jaisalmer Fort is a massive sandstone fortress situated in the heart of Jaisalmer city in Rajasthan. Built in the 12th century by the Rajput ruler Rawal Jaisal, the fort is also known as the \"Golden Fort\" or \"Sonar Qila\" due to its golden hue at sunset. The fort has several ornate temples, palaces, and havelis (traditional Indian mansions) within its walls, and the narrow streets lined with shops selling colorful handicrafts, textiles, and jewelry are a treat for visitors.\r\n\r\nPushkar Lake in Pushkar: The Pushkar Lake is a sacred lake situated in the town of Pushkar in Rajasthan. According to Hindu mythology, the lake was created by Lord Brahma, and taking a dip in its holy waters is believed to wash away one\'s sins. The lake is surrounded by several ghats (steps leading to the water) and more than 50 temples, including the famous Brahma Temple. The town of Pushkar also hosts an annual Camel Fair, which attracts tourists from around the world.', '2700 km', '46 hours by road, 2 hours by flight', 'To travel from Kerala to Rajasthan, you can take a flight to Jaipur or Udaipur, both of which have international airports. Alternatively, you can also take a train or a bus to reach Jaipur, which is well-connected to major cities in India. If you choose to travel by road, you can take National Highway 44, which passes through Bangalore, Hyderabad, and Mumbai, and ends in Jaipur. Along the way, you will come across beautiful landscapes, bustling cities, and charming towns that offer a glimpse into the rich cultural diversity of India.', 'Rajasthan is a popular destination among tourists from all over the world, thanks to its numerous tourist attractions that cater to all interests. One of the most famous tourist places in Rajasthan is the Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, which is a unique five-story building with over 900 windows that were once used by women of the royal household to observe street festivals without being seen by the public. Another popular tourist attraction in Rajasthan is the Jaisalmer Fort in Jaisalmer, which is a massive structure made of yellow sandstone and is known for its intricate carvings and beautiful architecture. Pushkar Lake in Pushkar is another must-visit place in Rajasthan, which is a sacred lake that is believed to have been created by Lord Brahma, according to Hindu mythology. The town of Pushkar is also known for its annual Pushkar Fair, which is a major tourist attraction and showcases the best of Rajasthan\'s culture and traditions.\r\n\r\nOverall, a trip from Kerala to Rajasthan promises to be an unforgettable experience, with its stunning architecture, rich history, and vibrant culture. Whether you choose to travel by air or by road, you are sure to come across numerous attractions that will leave you mesmerized and craving for more.'),
(8, 'Kerala', 'Punjab', 'Gokulll1.JPG,Gokulll2.JPG', 'Kochi, Bangalore, Hyderabad, Nagpur, Agra, Amritsar', 'Golden Temple in Amritsar, Wagah Border, Jallianwala Bagh', 'Other notable tourist attractions in Punjab include the Rambagh Gardens in Amritsar, which is a beautiful Mughal-style garden, and the Qila Mubarak Fort in Bathinda, which is an ancient fort that dates back to the 11th century. Additionally, if you\'re interested in experiencing Punjabi culture and cuisine, you should visit local markets and restaurants, where you can sample traditional dishes like makki ki roti and sarson ka saag, and shop for handicrafts and textiles.\r\n\r\nOverall, traveling from Kerala to Punjab offers a unique opportunity to experience the diversity of India, with its rich history, culture, and natural beauty. Whether you choose to travel by air or road, there are many famous and tourist places to visit and explore along the way.', '3000 km', '50 hours by road, 2 hours by flight', 'There are two main ways to reach Punjab from Kerala. The first is by air, with flights available from Kochi International Airport to Sri Guru Ram Dass Jee International Airport in Amritsar. This is the fastest option, with a travel time of only 4 hours, but it can be expensive. The second way to reach Punjab is by road, using National Highway 44. This route takes around 52 hours by car and passes through several major cities including Bangalore, Hyderabad, and Nagpur. You can either drive your own car or hire a taxi to travel along this route.', ' Kerala and Punjab are two culturally rich states in India, and traveling between them offers a glimpse of the country\'s diversity. If you\'re interested in exploring the history and culture of Punjab, there are several famous places that you should visit. The Golden Temple in Amritsar is a must-see attraction, as it is one of the most sacred sites in Sikhism and is known for its beautiful architecture and serene atmosphere. Another popular destination in Punjab is the Wagah Border, which is the only border crossing between India and Pakistan that is open to the public. Here, you can witness the daily flag-lowering ceremony, which is a display of military showmanship and patriotism. Finally, Jallianwala Bagh is a historic park in Amritsar that commemorates the site of the 1919 Amritsar Massacre, where hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed by British troops.'),
(9, 'Maharashtra', 'Delhi', 'Gateway_of_India.jpg,Jantar_Mantar_at_Jaipur.jpg', ' Maharastra, Gujarat, Rajasthan, Haryana', 'Gateway of India, Marine Drive, Red Fort, India Gate', 'Ajanta and Ellora Caves in Aurangabad, Jantar Mantar in Jaipur, Amer Fort in Jaipur', ' 1394 km', '23 hours by road, 2 hours by flight', ': To travel from Maharastra to Delhi, you can either take a flight or travel by road. There are several direct flights available from Mumbai, the capital city of Maharastra, to Delhi, which take around 2 hours. Alternatively, you can drive from Maharastra to Delhi, which takes around 23 hours, and pass through Gujarat, Rajasthan, and Haryana.\r\n\r\nIf you choose to travel by road, there are several interesting places to visit along the way. One of the most popular tourist attractions in Maharastra is the Ajanta and Ellora Caves in Aurangabad, which are ancient rock-cut caves featuring intricate carvings and paintings. In Rajasthan, you can visit the Jantar Mantar in Jaipur, an observatory built in the early 18th century that features large astronomical instruments. Another popular destination in Jaipur is the Amer Fort, a stunning hilltop fort built in the 16th century that offers panoramic views of the surrounding countryside.\r\n\r\nOnce you arrive in Delhi, you will find a wealth of cultural and historical sites to explore. Some of the must-see attractions in Delhi include the Red Fort, a historic fortress that was the residence of Mughal emperors; the India Gate, a war memorial honoring the Indian soldiers who died in World War I; and the Gateway of India, a famous landmark overlooking the Arabian Sea. If you are interested in experiencing Delhi\'s vibrant culture, you can visit the bustling markets of Chandni Chowk or take a stroll along the scenic Marine Drive.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, whether you choose to travel by road or by air, there are several interesting places to visit on the way from Maharastra to Delhi. From the Ajanta and Ellora Caves in Aurangabad to the historic sites of Delhi, there is something for everyone to enjoy on this journey.', 'Maharashtra, located in the western region of India, is a state rich in history and culture. From bustling cities to serene hill stations, Maharashtra has something to offer for every type of traveler. Delhi, the capital of India, is a vibrant city with a rich history. It is home to numerous monuments, temples, and museums, including the famous India Gate, Red Fort, and Qutub Minar. The city is well-connected by road, rail, and air and can be reached easily from Maharashtra. Traveling from Maharashtra to Delhi is a great way to explore the diversity of India and experience the country\'s unique blend of old and new.'),
(10, 'Maharashtra', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Ahilya_Ghat_by_the_Ganges_Varanasi.JPG,Fatehput_Sikiri_Buland_Darwaza_gate.JPG', 'Pune, Nagpur, Varanasi', 'Taj Mahal in Agra, Fatehpur Sikri, Varanasi Ghats\r\n\r\n', 'The Taj Mahal is undoubtedly one of the most famous and popular tourist attractions in Uttar Pradesh, and it is definitely worth a visit. Another popular attraction is Fatehpur Sikri, a UNESCO World Heritage Site that was once the capital of the Mughal Empire. Varanasi is another must-visit destination in Uttar Pradesh, known for its beautiful ghats along the Ganges River, where you can witness ancient rituals and ceremonies.', 'Approximately 1,250 km', 'Approximately 20 hours by road, 2 hours by flight', 'The best way to reach Uttar Pradesh from Maharashtra is to take a flight to Chaudhary Charan Singh International Airport in Lucknow. Alternatively, you can take a train or drive on National Highway 44, which connects the two states. If you are driving, there are several cities along the way where you can stop for food and rest, including Pune and Nagpur. The journey by road can take up to 20 hours, so it is advisable to plan for multiple stops along the way to break up the journey and avoid fatigue.', 'Uttar Pradesh is a state with a rich cultural and historical heritage, and it is home to some of the most iconic and beloved landmarks in India. From the Taj Mahal to the ghats of Varanasi, there is no shortage of amazing places to visit and explore. Traveling from Maharashtra to Uttar Pradesh is relatively easy, whether you choose to take a flight or drive along National Highway 44. Along the way, you can stop in cities like Pune and Nagpur to rest and refuel. Once you arrive in Uttar Pradesh, you can immerse yourself in the beauty and history of this incredible state, visiting places like the Taj Mahal and Fatehpur Sikri, and taking in the unique culture and traditions of Varanasi.'),
(11, 'Maharashtra', 'Rajasthan', 'GANDHI_ASHRAM.jpg,Hawa_Mahal_east_facade.jpg', 'Mumbai, Ahmedabad, Udaipur, Jaipur', 'Gateway of India in Mumbai, Sabarmati Ashram in Ahmedabad, City Palace in Udaipur, Amber Fort in Jaipur', ' Rajasthan is a treasure trove of tourist attractions, from its majestic forts and palaces to its colorful markets and stunning natural landscapes. In Jaipur, you can visit the iconic Amber Fort, which offers breathtaking views of the city. You can also explore the City Palace, a magnificent complex of palaces and courtyards that was once the seat of the Maharaja of Jaipur. In Udaipur, you can visit the City Palace, which overlooks the beautiful Lake Pichola. Other must-see attractions in Rajasthan include the Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, the Jaisalmer Fort in Jaisalmer, and the Pushkar Lake in Pushkar.', 'Approximately 1,200 km', '18-20 hours by road, 1.5 hours by flight', 'The best way to reach Rajasthan from Maharashtra is by taking a flight to Jaipur or Udaipur. Both cities have well-connected airports and are ideal entry points for exploring the state. Alternatively, you can also take a train or bus from Mumbai to Jaipur or Udaipur. The train journey takes around 16-18 hours, while a bus journey takes around 22-24 hours.', 'Rajasthan is a land of royal palaces, majestic forts, and vibrant culture. With its rich history and stunning landscapes, it is a must-visit destination for anyone interested in exploring the beauty of India. From the bustling streets of Mumbai to the tranquil lakes of Udaipur, this journey will take you through a range of experiences, each more captivating than the last. In Rajasthan, you will find a mix of old and new, where ancient traditions and modern lifestyles blend seamlessly together. Whether you want to marvel at the beauty of historic palaces or explore the colorful markets of Jaipur, there is something for everyone in this magical state.'),
(12, 'Maharashtra', 'Punjab', 'Jantar_Mantar_at_Jaipur (1).jpg,Chandigarh_Lake.jpg', 'Maharashtra: Mumbai, Pune\r\nRajasthan: Jaipur\r\nHaryana: Ambala\r\nPunjab: Chandigarh, Amritsar', 'Gateway of India, Mumbai\r\nShaniwar Wada Palace, Pune\r\nCity Palace, Jaipur\r\nAmber Fort, Jaipur\r\nSukhna Lake, Chandigarh\r\nGolden Temple, Amritsar', 'Elephanta Caves, Mumbai\r\nLonavala Hill Station, Pune\r\nAjanta and Ellora Caves, Aurangabad\r\nHawa Mahal, Jaipur\r\nJantar Mantar, Jaipur\r\nRanthambore National Park, Sawai Madhopur\r\nWagah Border, Amritsar', '1,751 km', '24 hours by road', 'The best way to reach Punjab from Maharashtra is by taking a direct flight from Mumbai to Chandigarh or Amritsar. Alternatively, you can take a train from Mumbai to Delhi, and then continue your journey to Punjab by taking a connecting train or hiring a private cab.\r\n\r\nIf you prefer to travel by road, the most popular route is via National Highway 48, which connects Mumbai to Delhi. From Delhi, you can take National Highway 44 to reach Chandigarh or Amritsar. The journey by road takes around 27 hours and offers stunning views of the countryside.', 'The journey from Maharashtra to Punjab takes you through some of the most vibrant cities and beautiful natural landscapes in India. Starting from the bustling city of Mumbai, you can explore the historic Gateway of India or take a ferry to the nearby Elephanta Caves. The next stop is Pune, known for its rich history and beautiful architecture, including the impressive Shaniwar Wada Palace.\r\n\r\nFrom here, the journey takes you to the Pink City of Jaipur, where you can explore the majestic City Palace and Amber Fort, and experience the vibrant culture of Rajasthan. The journey then takes you through the lush green hills of Haryana to the planned city of Chandigarh, where you can relax by the serene Sukhna Lake.\r\n\r\nFinally, the journey ends in the holy city of Amritsar, where you can visit the iconic Golden Temple and witness the patriotic fervor at the Wagah Border. Overall, this journey is a perfect mix of history, culture, and natural beauty, and is sure to leave you with memories that will last a lifetime.'),
(13, 'Goa', 'Delhi', 'Qutub.jpg,Tomb_of_Humayun_Delhi.jpg', 'Mumbai, Vadodara, Udaipur, Jaipur, Agra', ' Delhi is a city that is steeped in history and culture. It is home to a plethora of famous places that are worth visiting. One of the most iconic landmarks of Delhi is the Red Fort, a UNESCO World Heritage Site that was built in the 17th century by the Mughal emperor, Shah Jahan. The Qutub Minar is another famous monument in Delhi, known for its impressive architecture and intricate carvings. Humayun\'s Tomb is also a must-visit, which is the final resting place of the Mughal emperor, Humayun. The India Gate, a war memorial dedicated to Indian soldiers who died in World War I, is also a popular tourist spot.', 'There are plenty of tourist places to visit in Delhi, which are a testament to the city\'s rich culture and history. The Jama Masjid, one of the largest mosques in India, is a stunning example of Mughal architecture and is worth visiting for its intricate design and decoration. Another popular tourist spot is the Lotus Temple, which is known for its unique shape and serene environment. The Akshardham Temple, a grand Hindu temple, is also a must-visit, featuring stunning architecture and beautiful gardens. Additionally, the vibrant markets of Delhi, such as Chandni Chowk, are perfect for those who enjoy shopping and trying out local street food.\r\n\r\nOverall, traveling from Goa to Delhi is a wonderful opportunity to explore India\'s diverse culture and heritage. With a range of famous places and tourist spots to visit, Delhi is a city that should not be missed. Whether you choose to travel by road or air, be prepared to be amazed by the beauty and history of this incredible city.', '1500 KM', '24 hours', 'If you are planning to travel from Goa to Delhi, you have two options - by road or by air. The road journey from Goa to Delhi is a long one, taking around 31 hours to cover the distance of 1964 km. The most popular route is via the NH 48 and NH 44, passing through Mumbai and Agra. Alternatively, you can take a flight from Goa to Delhi, which takes around 2 hours. Indira Gandhi International Airport is the major airport in Delhi, which is well-connected to major cities in India and abroad.', 'Delhi, the capital of India, is known for its rich history, culture, and architecture. Some of the famous landmarks to visit in Delhi are Red Fort, India Gate, and Qutub Minar. Red Fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and was the residence of Mughal emperors for nearly 200 years. India Gate is a war memorial that honors the Indian soldiers who died in World War I. Qutub Minar is a 73-metre tall minaret made of red sandstone and marble, located in the Qutub complex.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, Goa is known for its stunning beaches, vibrant nightlife, and unique blend of Indian and Portuguese cultures. Some of the must-visit places in Goa include Anjuna Beach, Baga Beach, Calangute Beach, and Fort Aguada. Moving further north, Jaipur, also known as the Pink City, is a city of palaces and forts, and famous for its Hawa Mahal and Amber Fort. Agra is home to the iconic Taj Mahal, which is one of the Seven Wonders of the World and a UNESCO World Heritage Site.\r\n\r\nOverall, whether you choose to travel by road or by air, this journey from Goa to Delhi will take you through some of the most beautiful places in India and give you a glimpse of the diverse culture and heritage of the country.'),
(14, 'Goa', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Khajuraho_Group_of_Monuments.jpg,Orchha_Fort_and_Bridge.jpg', 'Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh', 'Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, Fatehpur Sikri', 'Khajuraho Temples, Orchha Fort, Varanasi Ghats', '1200 KM', '18 hours', 'The best way to travel from Goa to Uttar Pradesh is by taking a flight to Delhi or Lucknow, depending on your final destination. From Goa, you can take a direct flight to Delhi or Lucknow, which will take approximately 2.5 hours. Alternatively, you can take a train from Goa to Delhi or Lucknow, with multiple options available daily. The journey by train will take around 24-30 hours, depending on the route and the train you choose. If you prefer road trips, you can drive from Goa to Uttar Pradesh, which will take approximately 28 hours and will pass through Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh before reaching Uttar Pradesh.', 'Goa and Uttar Pradesh are two very different states, with their own unique cultures and attractions. Goa is known for its beautiful beaches, nightlife, and Portuguese influence, while Uttar Pradesh is known for its rich history, ancient monuments, and religious significance. A trip from Goa to Uttar Pradesh will take you on a journey through some of the most beautiful and diverse landscapes in India. Along the way, you will pass through Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh, two states that are also filled with historical and cultural treasures.\r\n\r\nOnce you arrive in Uttar Pradesh, there are numerous tourist attractions to explore. The Taj Mahal in Agra is one of the most famous landmarks in India and is a must-see for anyone visiting the country. Agra Fort, another popular attraction, is a UNESCO World Heritage site and a testament to the power and grandeur of the Mughal Empire. Fatehpur Sikri is another historic site in Uttar Pradesh, known for its beautiful architecture and design.\r\n\r\nIf you are interested in exploring more of Uttar Pradesh\'s history and culture, there are many other sites to visit, such as the Khajuraho Temples, which are known for their intricate carvings and sculptures; the Orchha Fort, which offers a glimpse into the region\'s rich medieval history; and the ghats of Varanasi, which are considered some of the most sacred places in India.'),
(15, 'Goa', 'Rajasthan', 'Jaisalmer_forteresse.jpg,Udaipur_City_Palace.jpg', ' Maharashtra, Gujarat, Rajasthan', 'Hawa Mahal, Jaisalmer Fort, Udaipur City Palace', 'Rajasthan is a land of rich history, culture, and heritage, and there are many places to visit in the state. Hawa Mahal in Jaipur is a famous landmark known for its intricate architecture, and it is a must-visit place for anyone traveling to Rajasthan. Jaisalmer Fort, also known as the Golden Fort, is another popular tourist attraction in the state, with its stunning sandstone walls and intricate carvings. The Udaipur City Palace is a majestic palace located on the banks of Lake Pichola in Udaipur, and it is known for its impressive architecture and intricate design. Other popular tourist places in Rajasthan include the Thar Desert, the Ajmer Sharif Dargah, and the Dilwara Temples in Mount Abu.', '1000 KM', '14 hours', 'There are two main ways to travel from Goa to Rajasthan. The first option is to take a flight from Goa International Airport to Jaipur International Airport, which takes around 3 hours. Alternatively, you can take a road trip by driving on National Highway 48 from Goa to Jaipur, passing through Maharashtra and Gujarat. This journey takes around 24 hours, and there are many interesting stops along the way, including Ahmedabad, which is known for its vibrant culture and delicious food.', 'Traveling from Goa to Rajasthan is an exciting journey that takes you through many diverse landscapes and cultural experiences. Whether you choose to fly or drive, you will have the opportunity to explore many interesting places along the way, including Ahmedabad in Gujarat, which is known for its rich history and delicious food. Once you arrive in Rajasthan, you will be amazed by the state\'s rich heritage, vibrant culture, and stunning architecture, with famous landmarks like the Hawa Mahal, Jaisalmer Fort, and Udaipur City Palace showcasing the beauty of the region. With so many interesting tourist places to visit in Rajasthan, this state is a must-see destination for anyone traveling to India.'),
(16, 'Goa', 'Punjab', 'pichola.jpg,Chandra_Mahal_City_Palace.jpg', 'Goa,\r\nMumbai,\r\nAhmedabad,\r\nUdaipur,\r\nJaipur,\r\nAgra,\r\nNew Delhi,\r\nAmritsar,\r\nPunjab', 'Gateway of India, Mumbai: A historical landmark and iconic monument in Mumbai, the Gateway of India is a must-visit attraction for anyone travelling to Maharashtra.\r\n\r\nSabarmati Ashram, Ahmedabad: The famous ashram of Mahatma Gandhi, Sabarmati Ashram is a peaceful retreat in the midst of the bustling city of Ahmedabad.\r\n\r\nLake Pichola, Udaipur: One of the most beautiful lakes in India, Lake Pichola is a popular tourist spot in Udaipur. You can enjoy a boat ride or take a walk around the lake to soak in the beauty of the place.', 'City Palace, Jaipur: The City Palace in Jaipur is a magnificent palace complex that houses a museum and several stunning courtyards and gardens.\r\n\r\nTaj Mahal, Agra: One of the most famous monuments in the world, the Taj Mahal is a must-visit for anyone travelling to Agra. The stunning white marble mausoleum is a symbol of love and an architectural marvel.\r\n\r\nRed Fort, Delhi: A UNESCO World Heritage Site, the Red Fort is a massive fortress in the heart of Delhi that dates back to the Mughal era.\r\n\r\nGolden Temple, Amritsar: The holiest shrine for Sikhs, the Golden Temple in Amritsar is a beautiful and peaceful place that attracts visitors from all over the world', '900 KM', '12 hours', 'By Air: The fastest and most convenient way to reach Punjab from Goa is by taking a direct flight from Goa International Airport to Sri Guru Ram Dass Jee International Airport in Amritsar. From Amritsar, you can take a taxi or a bus to reach your final destination in Punjab.\r\n\r\nBy Train: There are no direct trains between Goa and Punjab, so you\'ll have to take a train to Mumbai and then take a connecting train to Punjab. Alternatively, you can also take a train to New Delhi and then take a connecting train to Punjab.\r\n\r\nBy Road: You can drive or hire a taxi from Goa to Punjab, but it\'s a long and tiring journey. It\'s recommended to take breaks and stopovers along the way.', 'As you start from Goa, the first stop could be the city of Mumbai, also known as the financial capital of India. Mumbai is known for its iconic landmarks like the Gateway of India, Marine Drive, and the Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus. From Mumbai, you can take a flight or train to Delhi, which is the next stop on your journey. Delhi, the capital city of India, is known for its rich history, culture, and cuisine. Some of the must-visit places in Delhi include the Red Fort, Qutub Minar, India Gate, and Jama Masjid.\r\n\r\nFrom Delhi, you can head towards Agra, home to the iconic Taj Mahal. The Taj Mahal is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the Seven Wonders of the World. The beautiful white marble monument is a symbol of love and attracts tourists from all over the world.\r\n\r\nNext, you can head towards Jaipur, also known as the Pink City. Jaipur is famous for its magnificent palaces, forts, and temples. Some of the must-visit places in Jaipur include the Hawa Mahal, City Palace, Amber Fort, and Jantar Mantar.\r\n\r\nFrom Jaipur, you can head towards Amritsar, the holy city of the Sikhs. Amritsar is known for the Golden Temple, also known as Harmandir Sahib, which is the holiest shrine for the Sikhs. The city is also known for its delicious food, especially the famous Amritsari Kulcha.\r\n\r\nThe journey from Goa to Punjab is an exciting one as it takes you through different states, cultures, and traditions, allowing you to experience the diversity of India. Whether it\'s the beaches of Goa or the holy city of Amritsar, there is something for everyone on this journey.');

